{
  "answer": "**Bṛhaspati Smṛti** (unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070) provides the most detailed treatment of court structure and procedure in the corpus.[^1] Chapter 1 outlines the establishment of courts (e.g., in fortresses, facing east, with garlands and seats), kinds of courts (stationary, non-stationary, sealed, directed), assessors (7, 5, or 3 learned Brahmins), the king's role, officers (accountant, scribe), protective measures for litigants, order of proceedings (plaint, reply, evidence, decision), and rituals (imagining gods present, placing gold/fire/water).[^2]\n\n**Nārada Smṛti** (unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2) discusses court assembly, qualities of assessors (learned, impartial), their duties, and procedure (e.g., examining plaints, replies, evidence).[^3] It emphasizes the king's oversight with assessors and scribes.\n\n**Kātyāyana Smṛti** (unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2) briefly notes the king sitting with chief judge, ministers, Brahmins, priest, and assessors for judgments.[^4]\n\n**Āṅgirasa Smṛti** (unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1) mentions courts indirectly via judicial roles, but lacks detail on structure.[^5]\n\nFrench works like Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation* reference \"tribunals\" in modern contexts (e.g., special courts for slaves), but not ancient courtroom procedure.[^6]\n\nNo other works (e.g., poetry like Iqbal or Cynewulf) discuss this substantively; \"court\" appears metaphorically.\n\n[^1]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Ch. 1, paragraphs [p-ad41e5](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-ad41e5), [p-bf0a6b](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-bf0a6b), [p-7535d2](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-7535d2), [p-ef9590](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-ef9590), [p-8e89d7](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-8e89d7).\n\n[^3]: *Nārada Smṛti*, Ch. 1 (\"Mātṛkā 3\"), [full chapter](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/).\n\n[^4]: *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, Ch. 5, paragraph [p-3114b8](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/05/translation/#p-3114b8).\n\n[^5]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-86fa77).\n\n[^6]: E.g., *Traité de Législation: VOL IV*, Ch. 20, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/20/translation/#p-5b1e6b).",
